  <h1>Rodkeshia Clifton - Cybersecurity Portfolio</h1>

  <section>
    <h2>🔐 Project 1: Detecting Brute-Force Attacks Using Splunk</h2>
    <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Set up and use Splunk to monitor Windows event logs and detect brute-force login attempts.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools Used:</strong> Splunk, Windows 10 VM, Event Viewer</p>
    <p><strong>Methodology:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Installed Splunk Enterprise in a local lab environment.</li>
      <li>Configured a Windows 10 virtual machine to generate event logs.</li>
      <li>Collected and filtered security logs using Splunk Universal Forwarder.</li>
      <li>Queried Event ID 4625 for failed login attempts.</li>
      <li>Created dashboards and alerts to visualize brute-force attack patterns.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Improved SIEM skills and detection techniques.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>🛡️ Project 2: Vulnerability Assessment with Nessus</h2>
    <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Identify vulnerabilities on a test system using Nessus and provide recommendations for remediation.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools Used:</strong> Nessus Essentials, Kali Linux, Windows 10 VM</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Deployed Nessus to scan a Windows-based environment.</li>
      <li>Reviewed identified vulnerabilities and their severity levels.</li>
      <li>Interpreted CVSS scores and analyzed potential risks.</li>
      <li>Documented vulnerabilities and proposed mitigation steps.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gained experience with vulnerability management tools.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>🤟 Project 3: TryHackMe Incident Response Simulation</h2>
    <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Perform blue team activities in simulated threat environments and investigate security incidents.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools Used:</strong> TryHackMe, Wireshark, Splunk, Windows Logs</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Completed "Blue Primer" and "Security Operations" rooms.</li>
      <li>Analyzed logs to identify unauthorized activity and threats.</li>
      <li>Used Wireshark to examine network packets and extract IOCs.</li>
      <li>Documented findings and recommended response actions.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Applied theoretical knowledge in simulated environments.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>🔧 Project 4: Linux System Hardening</h2>
    <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Secure a Linux machine by applying hardening practices and auditing configurations.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools Used:</strong> Ubuntu, SSH, UFW, Auditd</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Implemented secure SSH configurations and disabled root login.</li>
      <li>Enabled UFW to manage firewall rules.</li>
      <li>Installed and configured Auditd to track system activity.</li>
      <li>Removed unnecessary services and applied updates.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Improved knowledge of Linux system security.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>📄 Project 5: Cybersecurity Policy Development</h2>
    <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Create a foundational security policy for a small business or home lab.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools Used:</strong> MS Word, NIST SP 800-53, CIS Controls</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Reviewed NIST and CIS frameworks for best practices.</li>
      <li>Drafted sections on access control, password policy, acceptable use, and incident handling.</li>
      <li>Structured the document for professional readability and clarity.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Demonstrated ability to translate frameworks into working policies.</p>
  </section>

